&lt;h3&gt;Shabbat Parashat B&#039;shalach&lt;br /&gt;
	Shabbat Shirah&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;General Notes&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Parashat B&#039;shalach is called Shabbat Shirah because it includes Shirat Hayam, or the Song of the Sea. The Israelites sing Shirat Hayam to celebrate crossing the Sea of Reeds and to praise God for subduing the Egyptians.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;Shacharit&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We sing a special melody for parts of Shirat Hayam (15:1-19). Part or all of each of the following verses is chanted to the special melody: 15:1, 2, 3, 6, 11, 16, 18. 15:21 is also chanted to the Shirat Hayam melody. Some congregations have the custom for the reader to chant each phrase and for the congregation to repeat that phrase or to respond with the next phrase. For the Shirat Hayam melody, see ATC 76.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;Shacharit Torah Reading - Traditional&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Exodus 13:17-17:16 (P 278, RP 434, WTC 381)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;7 Aliyot&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;Shacharit Haftarah - Traditional&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Judges 4:4-5:31 (P 703, RP 462)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;Mincha Torah Reading&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Exodus 18:1-12 (P 508, RP 471, WTC 409)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;3 Aliyot&lt;/p&gt;
